that we've been working on around Posit Team and our related offerings. To kick this session off,

00:00:17.760 --> 00:00:24.320
I want to talk a little bit about why we've built these things in particular, Workbench,

00:00:24.320 --> 00:00:31.520
Package Manager, and Connect. And I want to ask and answer the question, why do they exist?

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:38.400
Why these things? Well, one of the reasons they exist is our mission. If you're here at Posit

00:00:38.400 --> 00:00:44.720
Conf, you likely know about our mission at Posit, which is to create free and open source software

00:00:45.279 --> 00:00:50.400
that we fund this mission through the sales of our commercial product offerings.

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:57.439
And I personally, but we all hope that this mission resonates with you, but it doesn't answer my

00:00:57.439 --> 00:01:05.519
question, which is why do we build what we build? If our goal is to create products that are loved

00:01:05.519 --> 00:01:12.239
and valued by all our customers, we have to start, I think, by acknowledging the value that you can

00:01:12.239 --> 00:01:19.440
get from open source at no cost. You don't need to buy anything from us to get this value. You

00:01:19.519 --> 00:01:25.279
don't even need to be an expert in data science or R or Python to start getting value from open

00:01:25.279 --> 00:01:31.839
source. So how do we add on top of that? It's a very high bar. How do we build things that can

00:01:31.839 --> 00:01:40.160
add value on top of something that's already so powerful? Well, our approach is to go about this

00:01:40.160 --> 00:01:46.160
by solving problems for organizations, particularly organizations that have questions about how to

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:53.599
realize the value of open source at scale. And these questions tend to come to us in two flavors.

00:01:53.599 --> 00:01:59.199
There's the practical concerns that are coming from our users, and those folks want to know

00:01:59.199 --> 00:02:06.000
things like how will they get access to data? How will they make use of AI? How do they distribute

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:12.160
their work, automate things, collaborate with others, and integrate across other systems that

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:18.000
they need and want to use at their organization? And then we've got compliance concerns. These

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:24.479
folks like IT and SecOps groups who want to know, like, what is this that's happening inside of our

00:02:24.479 --> 00:02:30.880
organization? How do we secure and support these systems? How do we audit, govern? How do we control

00:02:30.880 --> 00:02:36.880
usage? How do we control costs? How do we manage the risk that this is going to bring inside to

00:02:36.880 --> 00:02:42.399
what we're doing? So you're going to hear throughout the session today these themes play out

00:02:42.399 --> 00:02:49.199
in basically every talk, and we've got many talks in this session, because this is the reason why

00:02:49.199 --> 00:02:55.679
our commercial products exist. They aim to be the solution or a collection of solutions to these

