00:19:18.400 --> 00:19:22.560
Integrate single sign-on for, so you can actually, you know, give user level access to those

00:19:22.560 --> 00:19:25.359
who want to have elevated privileges to Package Manager.

00:19:25.359 --> 00:19:29.599
And then unlimited federated identity providers for that seamless integration with external

00:19:29.599 --> 00:19:30.000
systems.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:32.959
Big excitement about this.

00:19:32.959 --> 00:19:36.800
This is all available now in the latest release of Package Manager that just went out last

00:19:36.800 --> 00:19:37.040
week.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:42.959
It is, most of these features are the Package Manager advanced tier, though simple token

00:19:42.959 --> 00:19:46.000
based repository authentication is available at the enhanced tier.

00:19:47.920 --> 00:19:52.560
So right now on the client side, so browser and remote CLI login is available now.

00:19:52.560 --> 00:19:56.239
Python package tooling works really great with PIP and UV if you're using a Python

00:19:56.239 --> 00:19:57.439
authenticated repository.

00:19:58.400 --> 00:20:05.119
Coming soon, more deeper R client support, so I realized that, you know, Python is first

00:20:05.119 --> 00:20:05.760
tier.

00:20:05.760 --> 00:20:09.920
R is coming soon, mainly because, you know, R, the R engine itself is actually doesn't

00:20:09.920 --> 00:20:11.839
have any sort of built-in authentication mechanism.

00:20:11.839 --> 00:20:15.520
So we're having to build a lot more tooling around that to make it more seamless there.

00:20:15.520 --> 00:20:19.439
But we're working on integrations that will make it very seamless for this work with

00:20:19.439 --> 00:20:24.959
Workbench, Connect, Positron, as well as on the open source tooling side through integrations

00:20:25.040 --> 00:20:28.319
with like the Pack package to make that process simpler there, too.

00:20:28.880 --> 00:20:34.319
As well as kind of looking at that same federation auth route for authenticating for if you're

00:20:34.319 --> 00:20:40.160
using Git builders and Package Manager rather than having to configure HTTPS or SSH keys

00:20:40.160 --> 00:20:43.359
to authenticate with your Git builders.

00:20:44.160 --> 00:20:47.599
So love to talk to you more if you're interested in this.

00:20:47.599 --> 00:20:50.160
Always looking for people to try these things out as soon as we get them out there.

00:20:50.160 --> 00:20:53.599
Feel free to stop by the lounge and we'd love to talk with any of our engineers or

00:20:53.599 --> 00:20:56.479
myself out there about the new features in Package Manager.

00:20:57.599 --> 00:21:01.760
I'm going to shift gears now to another initiative we've been working on at Posit

00:21:01.760 --> 00:21:03.280
here that we're calling Chronicle.

00:21:03.920 --> 00:21:09.599
And so Chronicle is a new tool that we've developed to really help all of our Posit

00:21:09.599 --> 00:21:14.560
team customers understand their usage of the product to really gain insights in making

00:21:14.560 --> 00:21:19.199
sure that you're actually using it to the best value that you've intended.

00:21:20.560 --> 00:21:22.640
So why did we build Chronicle?

00:21:22.640 --> 00:21:28.719
Well, many of you have told us of our commercial product customers that it's hard to get useful

00:21:28.719 --> 00:21:29.760
reports on usage.

00:21:29.760 --> 00:21:31.199
Data is scattered around.

00:21:31.199 --> 00:21:34.719
There's a combination of lots of different features around for doing that.

00:21:34.719 --> 00:21:38.640
But you really want to understand, again, what usage and value you're getting out of

00:21:38.640 --> 00:21:39.599
the products.

00:21:39.599 --> 00:21:44.640
So with Chronicle, we're really focusing on exploring that long-term usage.

00:21:44.640 --> 00:21:46.880
So it's not just what's happening today.

00:21:46.880 --> 00:21:48.719
What's the current state of my system?

00:21:48.719 --> 00:21:52.160
But really, how has that usage changed, for example, over the past year?

00:21:52.160 --> 00:21:53.839
And is my usage growing?

00:21:53.839 --> 00:21:56.160
Are we actually seeing a lot more users?

00:21:56.160 --> 00:22:01.040
Are we seeing a lot more use of certain applications in Connect and really just kind of getting

00:22:01.040 --> 00:22:04.719
a good sense, holistic sense of our long-term value?

00:22:05.359 --> 00:22:11.199
And so what Chronicle does is we need to centralize and have a way to centralize all of that data

00:22:11.199 --> 00:22:16.560
across my Posit environments, whether that's a single Connect server or a whole multiple

00:22:16.560 --> 00:22:20.160
clusters and deployments across a dev test and production environment that you want to

00:22:20.160 --> 00:22:22.880
kind of see one kind of unified view of all that.

00:22:22.880 --> 00:22:28.239
And make it easy to view that data and build reports around it to understand.

00:22:29.119 --> 00:22:34.000
So as a kind of a quick overview, imagine you have your Workbench and Connect environments

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:34.719
here.

00:22:34.719 --> 00:22:39.680
For each of those, all you need to do is install what we call a Chronicle agent, which is just

00:22:39.680 --> 00:22:46.160
a small telemetry agent that essentially periodically scrapes using the APIs and

00:22:46.160 --> 00:22:52.239
metrics endpoints from the products to gather data and collect that periodically and then

00:22:52.239 --> 00:22:54.160
sends it to a central Chronicle server.

00:22:54.160 --> 00:22:58.400
And so Chronicle server just is a single server that just needs network access from all of

00:22:58.400 --> 00:23:02.160
the servers you want to supply data from in your environment.

00:23:02.160 --> 00:23:07.760
And it takes all that data in, collects it, organizes it and manages it so into a much

00:23:07.760 --> 00:23:14.560
more tabular format that makes it really more well-suited for building reports and analyzing

00:23:14.560 --> 00:23:18.719
and really trying to dig into the data more like many data scientists would want to do.

00:23:20.079 --> 00:23:24.160
So that data goes into a data store that is just really ultimately ends up as a collection

00:23:24.160 --> 00:23:29.520
of Parquet files that you can use either within Workbench, Connect, or even any other

00:23:29.520 --> 00:23:36.000
environment that you want to that has the capability of the Aero Apache, Aero Parquet

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:36.560
format there.

00:23:37.119 --> 00:23:40.239
And then from that, the reports are there.

00:23:40.239 --> 00:23:43.920
We are working on providing some reporting outside of the box with that there, but also

00:23:44.880 --> 00:23:51.359
everything from building your own custom reporting tooling around that as well as we like to

00:23:51.359 --> 00:23:51.920
do these days.

00:23:51.920 --> 00:23:56.880
Hook it up to your favorite LLM to crawl the data and spit out more interesting data there

00:23:56.880 --> 00:23:57.119
as well.

00:23:58.079 --> 00:24:00.079
So a couple questions.

00:24:00.079 --> 00:24:01.040
What happens to my data?

00:24:01.040 --> 00:24:03.680
We saw the agents in the scary world there.

00:24:03.680 --> 00:24:05.599
No, all your data stays inside your environment.

00:24:05.599 --> 00:24:06.160
We're not here.

00:24:06.160 --> 00:24:11.599
This is not a telemetry agent that Posit is collecting and reading all of your data.

00:24:11.680 --> 00:24:17.760
It stays in that data store that you decide whether that's in a local volume or an AWS S3.

00:24:18.319 --> 00:24:22.160
And then you get to choose who has access to it and what they have access to.

00:24:23.280 --> 00:24:25.119
Best question, how much does it cost?

00:24:25.119 --> 00:24:26.000
Absolutely nothing.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:30.079
This is the tool that we are providing to all of our existing Posit team customers.

00:24:31.439 --> 00:24:35.520
We want to actually make sure that you are getting the value out of the products that

00:24:35.520 --> 00:24:36.160
you do buy.

00:24:37.040 --> 00:24:39.599
And so there's no licensing fees.

00:24:39.599 --> 00:24:41.680
No additional license hoops to jump through.

00:24:41.680 --> 00:24:44.959
It's available to all of you who have any of those positive products today.

00:24:46.239 --> 00:24:47.839
Very easy to install.

00:24:48.560 --> 00:24:51.920
Most of our customers who have tried it out such far have all been able to get up and

00:24:51.920 --> 00:24:53.439
running in an hour.

00:24:53.439 --> 00:24:56.800
Obviously, depending on how many servers you're deploying it to, you have to get the agents

00:24:56.800 --> 00:24:57.599
deployed to.

00:24:57.599 --> 00:24:59.439
But in general, really straightforward.

00:24:59.439 --> 00:25:05.439
We focused entirely on making this minimal configuration and minimal pain to install.

00:25:06.880 --> 00:25:11.199
And best of all, as I mentioned earlier, you're not limited to the reports we provide.

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:14.560
For those who really want to dig into it, the data is there.

00:25:14.560 --> 00:25:17.359
We scrape a lot of data out of all of the products.

00:25:17.359 --> 00:25:18.239
We'll work with Sync Connect.

00:25:18.239 --> 00:25:20.880
Package Manager will be coming later, early next year.

00:25:20.880 --> 00:25:25.439
And we'll be able to get you access to everything you need to use the data how you want to use

00:25:25.439 --> 00:25:25.520
it.

00:25:26.319 --> 00:25:28.880
So I encourage you to check out our Getting Started Guide.

00:25:30.560 --> 00:25:33.199
URL's there or the ratsnap.qr code.

00:25:33.199 --> 00:25:38.400
And with that, I will hand it off to Kara Wu, who's going to talk more about the new

00:25:38.400 --> 00:25:39.520
exciting features in Connect.

00:25:48.160 --> 00:25:48.959
All right.

00:25:48.959 --> 00:25:49.680
Hi, everyone.

00:25:50.239 --> 00:25:51.359
I am Kara Wu.

00:25:51.359 --> 00:25:53.839
I'm a software engineer on the Connect team.

00:25:53.839 --> 00:25:57.680
And I'm really, really excited to be here today to talk about some of the new features

00:25:57.680 --> 00:25:58.959
that we have been working on.

00:25:58.959 --> 00:26:03.119
Particularly because they are features that I would have loved to have had in a past

00:26:03.119 --> 00:26:04.640
life when I was a Connect customer.

00:26:07.040 --> 00:26:11.839
And that feature set that I'm excited to talk to you about today is the ability of Connect

00:26:11.839 --> 00:26:14.719
to build container images within Connect itself.

00:26:16.079 --> 00:26:17.439
So it's 2025.

00:26:17.439 --> 00:26:21.119
And in 2025, people want to be able to run their software in containers.

00:26:21.839 --> 00:26:23.760
There are a lot of benefits to doing this.

00:26:24.479 --> 00:26:25.599
One is stability.

00:26:25.599 --> 00:26:27.760
Because container images are static.

00:26:29.040 --> 00:26:30.079
Standalone artifacts.

00:26:30.079 --> 00:26:36.560
They can continue to run even long after package versions have gone out of support.

00:26:36.560 --> 00:26:38.479
Or things have changed on your system.

00:26:38.479 --> 00:26:43.119
You can be sure that your container image is doing the exact same thing that it was.

00:26:44.319 --> 00:26:46.160
They're also important for repeatability.

00:26:46.800 --> 00:26:50.719
Because you can know, again, that what you're running right now is exactly the same as what

00:26:50.719 --> 00:26:52.000
you ran five years ago.

00:26:52.959 --> 00:26:54.800
They also provide traceability.

00:26:54.800 --> 00:27:01.760
Because as a standalone artifact, you can actually inspect the contents of the container

00:27:01.760 --> 00:27:07.280
image to see exactly what was run and sort of debug things at a deeper level.

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:13.520
And lastly, if you're an organization that is already using containers for other services

00:27:13.520 --> 00:27:19.119
or other products that you build, then you may have useful tooling already around containers

00:27:19.119 --> 00:27:26.079
such as security vulnerability scanning or other tools that hook into the very robust

00:27:26.079 --> 00:27:27.520
container ecosystem now.

00:27:30.239 --> 00:27:34.959
But can I get a show of hands of who in this room loves building and maintaining Docker

00:27:34.959 --> 00:27:35.359
images?

00:27:37.920 --> 00:27:38.239
Okay.

00:27:39.839 --> 00:27:40.000
Okay.

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:45.599
So we have three weirdos that the rest of you can know to watch out for as you go through

00:27:45.599 --> 00:27:46.079
the conference.

00:27:46.800 --> 00:27:47.119
No.

00:27:47.119 --> 00:27:51.920
So building and maintaining Docker images can be a huge pain and very onerous.

00:27:51.920 --> 00:27:57.280
And so what we're really excited to share is that soon Kinect will be able to build

00:27:57.280 --> 00:28:03.040
container images of your deployed content for you with no Docker image required.

00:28:04.319 --> 00:28:09.119
So as you may know, Kinect already has the ability to run content in containers with

00:28:09.119 --> 00:28:10.239
off host execution.

00:28:11.439 --> 00:28:15.040
And so I'll explain a little bit about how that works today and how this feature sort

00:28:15.040 --> 00:28:16.239
of takes it to the next level.

00:28:16.959 --> 00:28:23.359
So if I've got a Shiny application running in Kinect like this one, in order to get my

00:28:23.359 --> 00:28:28.959
code that I have written on my local laptop to Kinect, I deploy a bundle of my source

00:28:28.959 --> 00:28:33.119
code and a manifest that describes my environment to Kinect.

00:28:34.319 --> 00:28:40.560
And Kinect keeps track of those bundles so that it can sort of restore my environment,

00:28:40.560 --> 00:28:45.359
run the content, and also roll back to previous versions if needed.

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:51.280
So this is the view in Kinect of the bundles of this application that I have deployed.

00:28:52.479 --> 00:28:59.040
When I'm running off host execution, I will specify an execution environment that I want

00:28:59.040 --> 00:29:04.959
to use, which has a container image that has R and Python installed into it.

00:29:04.959 --> 00:29:09.920
And I know that if I deploy my bundle of content, it's going to go up to Kinect and

00:29:09.920 --> 00:29:14.000
something's going to happen in between that takes that execution environment image and

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:16.479
produces my application running in Kinect.

00:29:16.479 --> 00:29:19.920
But what happens in the middle is a little bit of a black box.

00:29:19.920 --> 00:29:23.599
And there's a lot of moving pieces to it, but at a high level, the important thing is

00:29:23.599 --> 00:29:30.400
that the package cache, so my R package dependencies or my Python package dependencies, as well

00:29:30.400 --> 00:29:35.920
as my content bundle that I have deployed, basically get mounted to a container, meaning

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:42.160
that they are made available, but they are not part of the image that is being launched.

00:29:42.160 --> 00:29:47.119
So we take the execution environment image, we sort of attach all of this stuff, and we

00:29:47.119 --> 00:29:50.479
get a container that's running in Kinect with my content.

00:29:50.479 --> 00:29:55.520
And this works really well, but it is ephemeral, because all of this stuff has to happen to

00:29:55.520 --> 00:30:00.239
make it work together, and if I come back a couple months from now, maybe the execution

00:30:00.239 --> 00:30:04.880
environments that are configured in my Kinect instance have changed, and so things may just

00:30:04.880 --> 00:30:07.920
be slightly different.

00:30:07.920 --> 00:30:12.400
So with the new containerization feature that we've been working on, Kinect will actually

00:30:12.400 --> 00:30:18.560
take that execution environment image and build an entirely new image that contains

00:30:18.560 --> 00:30:25.680
the dependencies and the content bundle within it, and push it to a container registry that

00:30:25.680 --> 00:30:31.920
I as a Kinect customer own and maintain, and then Kinect will be able to run that image

00:30:31.920 --> 00:30:37.599
more or less as is to serve the content, and what is really nice about this is that

00:30:37.599 --> 00:30:41.199
that is then very self-contained, because all of the dependencies on the content are

00:30:41.199 --> 00:30:46.880
within the image, and so execution environments may come and go, but that content is going

00:30:46.880 --> 00:30:49.119
to stay stable.

00:30:49.119 --> 00:30:58.079
So I'm going to now risk my life with a live demo of how all this is going to work.

00:30:58.160 --> 00:31:05.680
So here's that same application that's running in Kinect, and if I go over to my bundles,

00:31:05.680 --> 00:31:08.560
I can see I've got several bundles here deployed.

00:31:08.560 --> 00:31:12.640
The user experience, what a user's going to do to containerize a bundle is select the

00:31:12.640 --> 00:31:18.959
bundle that they want to containerize, click containerize, and then it's going to prompt

00:31:18.959 --> 00:31:23.599
with a confirmation, like are you sure that you want to do this, and that's because this

00:31:23.599 --> 00:31:27.119
containerization operation cannot be undone.

00:31:27.119 --> 00:31:32.959
It's a best practice to keep these images sort of immutable and static, so I will accept

00:31:32.959 --> 00:31:40.800
this and confirm, and then that is going to kick off a container build, and it's running

00:31:40.800 --> 00:31:48.959
through a bunch of logs, it's going to install my package dependencies, my content, and build

00:31:48.959 --> 00:31:54.560
all of the things that are needed for this content image to run, and then it is going

00:31:54.560 --> 00:32:06.719
to push it to a container registry, and at the end, it launches my Python Shiny application,

00:32:06.719 --> 00:32:16.000
and you can see in the bundle UI that now this bundle is showing up as containerized.

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:21.920
Everything else about this application looks exactly the same, but it is running that containerized

00:32:21.920 --> 00:32:27.040
bundle now instead of using the execution environment image, and I can prove that by

00:32:27.040 --> 00:32:30.959
removing all of the execution environments from the system and showing that this content

00:32:30.959 --> 00:32:40.160
still continues to run.

00:32:40.160 --> 00:32:42.160
So I have one execution environment here.

00:32:42.160 --> 00:32:51.280
I'm going to go ahead and delete it.

00:32:51.359 --> 00:32:55.280
And now I'll get a message saying that uncontainerized content is not going to be able to run on

00:32:55.280 --> 00:33:10.319
the system, but if I go back to my application, it still runs fine.

00:33:10.319 --> 00:33:14.160
Now as I mentioned, these images are getting pushed to a container registry.

00:33:14.160 --> 00:33:18.479
For security reasons, we're going to recommend that that registry only be accessible from

00:33:18.479 --> 00:33:24.079
Connect because it is not going to have the knowledge of permissions of who can access

00:33:24.079 --> 00:33:29.119
what content that Connect does, but at the end of the day, it is just a container registry,

00:33:29.119 --> 00:33:36.239
and so it is possible to pull that image and run it locally as you would any other.

00:33:36.239 --> 00:33:53.599
So I'm going to go ahead and find the image, which is linked right here, and if I go to

00:33:53.599 --> 00:34:13.840
a terminal, I can type and pull that image, and I can run it.

00:34:13.840 --> 00:34:35.360
And if I go back to my browser, that exact same content image is running locally.

00:34:35.360 --> 00:34:36.360
I could test it.

00:34:36.360 --> 00:34:37.360
I could debug it.

00:34:37.360 --> 00:34:43.760
I could do whatever I need to do.

00:34:43.760 --> 00:34:48.879
So some of you at this point may be looking at all of this and wondering, but wait, where's

00:34:48.879 --> 00:34:50.080
the Dockerfile?

00:34:50.080 --> 00:34:53.719
Where is the Dockerfile that defines the image that was built?

00:34:53.719 --> 00:34:58.159
And the answer is there is not one.

00:34:58.159 --> 00:35:01.399
For those of you who are less familiar with this, this is what a Dockerfile would sort

00:35:01.399 --> 00:35:02.399
of look like.

00:35:02.399 --> 00:35:07.959
You would need a file like this to define a container image to say what sort of base

00:35:07.959 --> 00:35:12.959
image you're building from, what packages you need to install, what system dependencies

00:35:12.959 --> 00:35:20.959
you need to copy over the source code of your application, and to specify what command launches

00:35:20.959 --> 00:35:23.040
your application when the container runs.

00:35:23.040 --> 00:35:28.399
This is a very simplified example, but these can get really long and complicated, and we

00:35:28.399 --> 00:35:35.080
did not feel that a publisher in Kinect would want to or should have to manage these Dockerfiles.

00:35:35.080 --> 00:35:37.560
And so there are no Dockerfiles.

00:35:37.560 --> 00:35:42.879
We have developed this containerization feature so that we are using cloud native build packs

00:35:42.879 --> 00:35:47.919
to generate container images just from the contents of the bundle and a little bit of

00:35:47.919 --> 00:35:50.120
metadata that Kinect adds to it.

00:35:50.120 --> 00:35:52.959
So no Dockerfile required.

00:35:52.959 --> 00:35:57.679
Instead we're using this open source specification that can build container images based off

00:35:57.679 --> 00:36:00.600
of application source code.

00:36:00.600 --> 00:36:09.159
So the way this works is that we will run all of these content bundles when you containerize

00:36:09.159 --> 00:36:10.159
a bundle.

00:36:10.159 --> 00:36:14.120
We will run it through what's called a detect phase, which is going to determine what build

00:36:14.120 --> 00:36:16.639
packs are applicable to build an image.

00:36:16.639 --> 00:36:21.800
So if you're deploying a Python application, there will be some Python version information

00:36:21.959 --> 00:36:23.959
in that bundle.

00:36:23.959 --> 00:36:30.800
If there may be a requirements.txt or if you're doing an R application, there will be R version

00:36:30.800 --> 00:36:31.800
information.

00:36:31.800 --> 00:36:33.399
There may be an RN block file.

00:36:33.399 --> 00:36:37.439
You might have both if you're doing a shiny app that uses reticulate.

00:36:37.439 --> 00:36:42.520
So we run through this detect phase to determine which build packs are applicable.

00:36:42.520 --> 00:36:48.800
And then we go through a build phase that runs the appropriate build packs for the content

00:36:48.800 --> 00:36:50.080
that is being built.

00:36:50.080 --> 00:36:55.360
So if there's Python content, then it's going to configure Python.

00:36:55.360 --> 00:36:57.600
It's going to pip install the requirements.

00:36:57.600 --> 00:37:02.080
If there's R content, it's going to configure R. It's going to install RN.

00:37:02.080 --> 00:37:06.080
It's going to have RN install the packages.

00:37:06.080 --> 00:37:12.040
And so based on the bundle itself, we can actually build these images without having

00:37:12.040 --> 00:37:15.800
to have an external file that sort of defines how they need to be built.

00:37:15.800 --> 00:37:20.080
So we've written our own custom build packs that can do this for the content types that

